'''Andrew D. (Andy) Braden''' (1916 – 1993) was an American economist, accountant, and Professor of Accountancy at [[Case Western Reserve University]], known for his work on accounting principles in the 1960s.<ref>Murphy, Mary Elizabeth. ''Managerial accounting.'' Van Nostrand, 1963.</ref><ref>Hastings, Paul Guiler. ''The management of business finance.'' Van Nostrand, 1966.</ref>
Braden received his BS in Education from [[Kent State University]], and obtained his [[Certified Public Accountant]] certificate. He started his academic career at the Case Western Reserve University in 1946 as instructor in Accounting.<ref>''Western Reserve University Bulletin,'' Vol. 51, Nr. 10 (1948), p. 12.</ref> There he taught accountancy for more than 40 years, and became Professor of Accountancy and director of the Accounting and MBA programs.<ref>[http://weatherhead.case.edu/support/honor-roll/braden The Andrew D. Braden Fund] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109220916/http://weatherhead.case.edu/support/honor-roll/braden |date=January 9, 2015 }}. . Accessed 09.01.2915.</ref> In 1962 he published his main work ''Accounting principles'', co-authored with Robert G. Allyn. In memory of his work Case Western initiated the Andrew D. Braden Professor of Accounting and Auditing-chair, and the Andrew D. Braden Fund.
== Selected publications == * Braden, Andrew D., and Robert G. Allyn. ''[https://archive.org/details/accountingprinci033067mbp Accounting principles].'' Van Nostrand, 1963.
;Articles, a selection: * Braden, Andrew D. "The Need for Simplicity in the Teaching of Accounting." Accounting Review (1954): 499-500. * Braden, Andrew D. "The Blackboard versus Projected Still Pictures in the Teaching of Accounting-An Experiment." ''Accounting Review'' (1954): 683-687.
