{{refimprove|date=November 2011}}
A '''perfect attendance award''' is traditionally given in [[United States|U.S.]] [[school]]s as a way to honor [[student]]s who have neither missed any days of nor been late to [[Class (education)|class]]. Supporters believe that the award promotes education by encouraging students to attend class whenever it is in session. However, some believe that offering a perfect attendance award promotes [[presenteeism]] and hurts public health by causing students to attend class when sick with a potentially contagious illness,<ref>{{cite web | last = Dutton<!-- name is from another, now-dead copy of the article; current page names no author. Correct? --> | first = Melissa Kossler | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Attendance: Less Than Perfect Can Be Even Better | work = | publisher = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]<!-- actually an Associated Press article; should that be the publisher? --> | date = 12 July 2011 | url = http://www.cbc.ca/backtoschool/2011/08/attendance-less-than-perfect-can-be-even-better.html | doi = | accessdate = 14 February 2014 }}</ref> while punishing those who make the decision to stay home to recover.
