{{Infobox scientist | name = Steven Sol Skiena | image = Steven_Skiena.jpg | image_size = 150px | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|01|30}} | nationality = [[United States]] | field = [[Computer science]] | work_institutions = [[Stony Brook University]] (1988–present) | alma_mater = [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Herbert Edelsbrunner]] }}
'''Steven Sol Skiena''' (born January 30, 1961) is a Distinguished Teaching Professor of [[Computer Science]] at [[Stony Brook University]].<ref>[https://www.cs.stonybrook.edu/Distinguished-Professor-Award-2009-Steven-Skiena Distinguished Teaching Professor Award: Steven Skiena] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004140152/https://www.cs.stonybrook.edu/Distinguished-Professor-Award-2009-Steven-Skiena |date=2017-10-04 }}, Stony Brook CS, accessed 2017-10-03.</ref> He was co-founder of [[General Sentiment]], a social media and news analytics company, and served as Chief Science Officer from 2009 to 2015.<ref>[http://www.generalsentiment.com/who-we-are.html General Sentiment personnel page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611000738/http://www.generalsentiment.com/who-we-are.html |date=2012-06-11 }}.</ref> His research interests include [[algorithm design]] and its applications to [[biology]]. Skiena is the author of several popular books in the fields of algorithms, programming, and mathematics. ''The Algorithm Design Manual'' is widely used as an undergraduate text in algorithms and within the tech industry for job interview preparation.<ref>[http://steve-yegge.blogspot.com/2008/03/get-that-job-at-google.html] [[Steve Yegge]]'s blog</ref> In 2001, Skiena was awarded the [[IEEE Computer Science and Engineering Undergraduate Teaching Award]] "for outstanding contributions to undergraduate education in the areas of algorithms and discrete mathematics and for influential textbook and software."<ref>[https://www.computer.org/web/awards/cse-steven-skiena Steven Skiena: 2001 Computer Science and Engineering Undergraduate Teaching Award], IEEE Computer Society, accessed 2017-10-03.</ref>
Skiena has worked on algorithmic problems in [[synthetic biology]], and, in particular, issues of optimal gene design for a given protein under various constraints. In collaboration with virologist [[Eckard Wimmer]], he has worked to computationally design synthetic viruses for use as [[attenuated vaccine]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Coleman | display-authors = etal | year = 2008 | title = Virus attenuation by genome-scale changes in codon pair bias | url = | journal = Science | volume = 320 | issue = 5884| pages = 1784–7 | doi = 10.1126/science.1155761 | pmid = 18583614 | pmc=2754401}}</ref> Their Synthetic Attenuated Virus Engineering (SAVE) approach has been validated in flu<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mueller | display-authors = etal | year = 2010 | title = Live attenuated influenza virus vaccines by computer-aided rational design.| journal = Nature Biotechnology | volume = 28 | issue = 7| pages = 723–6 | pmid = 20543832 | doi=10.1038/nbt.1636 | pmc=2902615}}</ref> and experiments with other viruses are ongoing. A popular account of this work appears in Dennis Shasha and Cathy Lazare's ''Natural Computing.''<ref>Natural Computing; Dennis Shasha and Cathy Lazare, W. W. Norton & Company, 2010.</ref>
Skiena played a role in the conception of the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[iPad]]. In 1988, Skiena and his team won a competition run by Apple to design the ''Computer of the Year 2000''.<ref>{{Cite journal | title = Tablet: Personal Computer in the Year 2000 | url = http://www.stephenwolfram.com/publications/academic/tablet-personal-computer-year-2000.pdf | journal = [[Communications of the ACM]] | volume = 31 | issue = 6 | date = June 1988 | pages = 638–648 | author1 = Bartlett W. Mel | author2 = Stephen M. Omohundro |authorlink2 = Stephen M. Omohundro | author3 = Arch D. Robison | author4 = Steven S. Skiena | author5 = Kurt H. Thearling | author6 = Kune T. Young | author7 = Stephen Wolfram | authorlink7 = Stephen Wolfram | doi=10.1145/62959.62960 }}</ref> Their design, a tablet featuring a touch screen, GPS, and wireless communications was similar in many regards to the iPad of 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/01/28/barron-tablet-post |url-access=limited |title=Apple's New Device Looks Like a Winner. From 1988 |author=James Barron |journal=New York Times |date=Jan 28, 2010}}</ref>
